        <li>Browser 2D Canvas API</li>
      </ul>
      <h3>Roles and Development</h3>
      <p>
        Created during employment at {{ COMPANY_FULLNAME }}, the making of this
        game involved being its software engineer and lead of concept design.
        <span
          title="Although I did make the road graphics and the lower-detail mountain graphic used as the bottom parallax layer."
          >The pixel art was created by another employee,</span
        >
        with project management duties being taken up by {{ ABBR }}&rsquo;s
        management. This game involved working collaboratively as a team,
        adhering to strict detail requirements, and ensuring deadlines were met
        for completion in 2020.
      </p>

      <p>
        {{ ABBR }} Racer was made in a custom TypeScript-based engine. Unlike
        later games, this one does not use any dependencies for rendering,
        instead relying on the native browser
        <a
          href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Canvas_API"
          title="I think if I made a game like this today I could pull off similar effects with shaders."
          target="_blank"
          >2D Canvas</a
        >
        API for all rendering needs. The Canvas API was also used to dynamically
        generate the road textures, which are stored in memory and manipulated
        to create a faux-3D effect.
      </p>

      <p>
        The game was originally intended to be longer, with multiple different
        areas which would transition into each other, just like in
        <em>Outrun.</em> While the code to handle this transition effect is in
        the final game, only one area is actually defined: the desert area.
      </p>

